Let $a = 2^{1001}-1$ and $b = 2^{1012}-1$. We can use the Euclidean algorithm to find the greatest common divisor of $a$ and $b$.

Step 1: Divide $b$ by $a$ and find the remainder.
\begin{align*}
b &= (2^{1012}-1) \\
&= (2^{1001} \cdot 2^{11}) - 1 \\
&= (2^{1001}-1) \cdot 2^{11} + (2^{11}-1)
\end{align*}

Step 2: Divide $a$ by the remainder from step 1 and find the new remainder.
\begin{align*}
a &= (2^{1001}-1) \\
&= (2^{11}-1) \cdot 2^{990} + (2^{990}-1)
\end{align*}

Step 3: Divide the remainder from step 1 by the remainder from step 2 and find the new remainder.
\begin{align*}
(2^{11}-1) &= (2^{990}-1) \cdot 2^2 + (2^2-1) \\
&= 3 \cdot 2^2 + 3
\end{align*}

Step 4: Divide the remainder from step 2 by the remainder from step 3 and find the new remainder.
\begin{align*}
(2^{990}-1) &= 3 \cdot 2^2 + 3
\end{align*}

Since the remainder is the same in steps 3 and 4, we can conclude that the greatest common divisor of $a$ and $b$ is $3$.
